            "html": "<p class=\"q-text qu-display--block\" style=\"box-sizing: border-box; margin-bottom: 0px; overflow-wrap: anywhere; word-break: break-word; direction: ltr; text-align: start;\"><span style=\"font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; background: none;\">I started on my own, and really enjoyed it. I could decide for myself what I wanted to do, and although I probably wasted months developing a decent workout, in the end that was more motivation to find the perfect workout for </span><span style=\"font-weight: normal; font-style: italic; background: none;\">me</span><span style=\"font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; background: none;\">. However, if you don't have enough motivation of your own, go to a gym and let them do it for you. Maybe a few bucks a month will be just the push you need. <br>People will tell you a lot of things. Always remember this. </span><span style=\"font-weight: normal; font-style: italic; background: none;\">Nothing anyone tells you will work perfectly for you. </span><span style=\"font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; background: none;\"> If they tell you to do the 5x5 workout, give it a try, but DO NOT be afraid to tweak it, or change it, or even discard it, if after a few weeks or months you see that it's not doing you enough good. Sometimes that change will be all that you need to do to get past a plateau. <br>I might add, don't diet. Eat right. Big difference. Basically, I eat what I want as long as my abs are still ok and I feel good. For this reason I seldom eat fried chicken. The results aren't pretty. Nuff said. <br>If you can, take supplements. Some people are going to down this, and that's ok. but seriously, my big gains started when I bought quality protein and creatine, and took it </span><span style=\"font-weight: normal; font-style: italic; background: none;\">precisely</span><span style=\"font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; background: none;\"> according to instructions, after my workout. <br>Just do what works for you man. Try it all on. Even if you don't suddenly become huge, you'll be fit, and that's what counts. <br>Also, kudos and ditto to Dhaval Mehta.</span></p>",
