            "html": "<p class=\"q-text qu-display--block\" style=\"box-sizing: border-box; margin-bottom: 1em; overflow-wrap: anywhere; word-break: break-word; direction: ltr; text-align: start;\"><span style=\"font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; background: none;\">A few more without getting too wordy:</span></p> <p class=\"q-text qu-display--block\" style=\"box-sizing: border-box; margin-bottom: 1em; overflow-wrap: anywhere; word-break: break-word; direction: ltr; text-align: start;\"><span style=\"font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; background: none;\"></span></p><ul class=\"q-box\" style=\"box-sizing: border-box; direction: ltr; overflow-wrap: break-word; list-style: disc; margin-bottom: 1em; margin-right: 2em;\"><li class=\"q-relative\" style=\"box-sizing: border-box; position: relative; margin-left: 2em; padding-bottom: 0.7em;\"><span style=\"font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; background: none;\">Start light and move up very gradually. Lifting too much too quickly is an awesome way to get injuries. You don't want those. </span></li><li class=\"q-relative\" style=\"box-sizing: border-box; position: relative; margin-left: 2em; padding-bottom: 0.7em;\"><span style=\"font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; background: none;\">Focus on maintaining good form and technique. I laugh at people who use false grips and don't use full range of motion (unless it's obvious that they are training a specific range).</span></li><li class=\"q-relative\" style=\"box-sizing: border-box; position: relative; margin-left: 2em; padding-bottom: 0.7em;\"><span style=\"font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; background: none;\">Focus on multi-joint and structural movements (e.g. bench, squat, deadlift). These movements use require more energy and engage more muscles. </span></li><li class=\"q-relative\" style=\"box-sizing: border-box; position: relative; margin-left: 2em; padding-bottom: 0px;\"><span style=\"font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; background: none;\">Make sure that your </span><span style=\"font-weight: bold; font-style: normal; background: none;\">total calorie load</span><span style=\"font-weight: normal; font-style: normal; background: none;\"> is big enough to support muscle growth. Don't be a gym simpleton and think that consuming a ton of protein is going to make you gain muscle faster; it will not. At the end of the day you need far less protein than you think; what matters most is the amount of total food energy you consume.</span></li></ul>",
